{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 20:40:30.843028", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall network health: Normal. End-to-end connectivity from user subnets to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is working, DNS resolution for the local zone is correct, and HTTP services (web0–web3 and the load balancer web99) are reachable with stable performance.\n- Security segmentation: Effective. Direct access from user subnets to backend web servers (20.200.0.0/24) is blocked, as designed.\n- Minor, non-impacting anomalies: Reverse DNS (PTR) queries for access-subnet IPs are refused by the DNS server; DHCP lease times on hosts are very short (likely lab default). One curl measurement artifact on the server_access_router showed near-zero timings.\n\nKey findings and evidence\n\n1) IP addressing, routing, and reachability\n- Representative access hosts obtained IP via DHCP and have correct default gateways:\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.10/24 via 10.1.1.1 (dynamic lease, valid_lft ~59s)\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.12/24 via 10.2.1.1 (dynamic lease, valid_lft ~55s)\n- Server access side:\n  - server_access_router bridges web, DNS, DHCP, and load balancer interfaces in br0, with IP 10.200.0.1/24. OSPF adjacencies present via 172.16.0.14/31; OSPF-learned routes exist for all 10.1.x and 10.2.x /24s.\n- Reachability within the enterprise (10.x.x.x):\n  - Bulk ping tests among 10.1/10.2 subnets show 0% loss, RTTs ~1–6 ms.\n- Reachability to server farm from hosts:\n  - HTTP to 10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6 (web0–web3) is successful from hosts with total time ~1.0–1.2 s and TTFB ~0.2–0.4 s.\n- Intended isolation of backend network:\n  - From host_1_1_1_1, ICMP to 20.200.0.2 returns “Destination Net Unreachable” from 10.1.1.1. Curl to http://20.200.0.2 times out (~1–3 s totals without connection). This confirms no route to 20.200.0.0/24 from access networks, as designed.\n\n2) DNS function (authoritative for local zone)\n- Hosts use DNS at 10.200.0.2 and successfully resolve:\n  - web0.local → 10.200.0.3; web1.local → 10.200.0.4; web2.local → 10.200.0.5; web3.local → 10.200.0.6; web99.local → 10.200.0.7\n- DNS server process listening:\n  - Bind/named is listening on 10.200.0.2:53 and 127.0.0.1:53.\n- Reverse DNS:\n  - Reverse lookup for 10.1.1.10 on dns_server is refused/non-recursive; not required for the stated service path but noted as an anomaly.\n\n3) HTTP services and load balancer\n- Web servers (front-ends) are listening on port 80 on all interfaces:\n  - web_server_0–3: tcp 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN\n- Load balancer (nginx) configuration:\n  - Nginx upstream “web99” includes 20.200.0.2:80, 20.200.0.3:80, 20.200.0.4:80; listener 0.0.0.0:80 proxy_pass to upstream.\n- Load balancer to backends connectivity:\n  - Curl from load_balancer to 20.200.0.[2–4] succeeds with total ~1.0–1.3 s, TTFB ~0.2–0.5 s.\n  - ARP on load_balancer shows neighbors for 20.200.0.2/.3/.4 on eth1, confirming L2 adjacency.\n- End-to-end user experience:\n  - Curl from both representative hosts to http://web99.local: totals ~1.0–1.1 s, stable across runs; indicates functional load-balanced service.\n\n4) OSPF and server-access routing\n- server_access_router routes include OSPF-learned 10.1.1.0/24, 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24 via 172.16.0.14 (core), and directly connected 10.200.0.0/24 on br0.\n- This aligns with the design: 10.200.0.0/24 is advertised to the enterprise; 20.200.0.0/24 remains isolated behind the load balancer (no enterprise route).\n\nAnomalies identified\n\nA) Backend network access from hosts\n- Observation: Hosts cannot ping or connect to 20.200.0.0/24 (e.g., ping/curl to 20.200.0.2 fails).\n- Assessment: Expected and desired per design (“backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts”). Not a fault.\n\nB) DNS reverse lookups refused\n- Observation: On dns_server, reverse lookup for 10.1.1.10 is REFUSED and recursion not available for 127.0.0.1.\n- Localization: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\n- Likely root cause: DNS server configured as non-recursive/authoritative-only with no PTR zones for 10.0.0.0/8; reverse lookups are not permitted or not defined.\n- Impact: No impact on forward resolution for local zone used by clients; informational.\n\nC) DHCP lease time is very short\n- Observation: Hosts show DHCP valid_lft around 55–59 seconds.\n- Localization: dhcp_server or DHCP relay config.\n- Likely root cause: Lab/test configuration using short lease timers (common in simulations).\n- Impact: None observed on reachability; potentially increased DHCP chatter; likely intentional for the environment.\n\nD) Measurement artifact on server_access_router curl to web99.local\n- Observation: curl timing on server_access_router to web99.local returned near-zero totals in the test output.\n- Localization: server_access_router or test harness.\n- Likely root cause: Tool output artifact (since the same path and services are confirmed healthy from multiple other vantage points).\n- Impact: None on actual service; treat as measurement anomaly.\n\nConclusion\n- No service-impacting anomalies detected. The network meets the described design objectives:\n  - OSPF distributes server farm reachability to the access subnets.\n  - DNS resolves local zone names correctly for clients.\n  - web0–web3 and web99 are reachable and responding with consistent performance.\n  - Backend web servers in 20.200.0.0/24 are appropriately isolated from direct host access, while the load balancer has full backend reachability.\n\n- Non-impacting issues include missing/disabled reverse DNS on the DNS server and very short DHCP lease timers, both likely intentional or acceptable in the current lab context.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 24324, "output_tokens": 5509, "total_tokens": 29833, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 23936}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3904}}}
